ons><abstract xml:lang="en" id="Abs1" abstract-type="Standfirst"><p id="Par1">Solar energy conversion is demonstrated in graphene-on-silicon solar cells.</p></abstract><custom-meta-group><custom-meta><meta-name>publisher-imprint-name</meta-name><meta-value>Nature Research</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-contains-esm</meta-name><meta-value>No</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-numbering-style</meta-name><meta-value>Unnumbered</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-registration-date-year</meta-name><meta-value>2010</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-registration-date-month</meta-name><meta-value>6</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-registration-date-day</meta-name><meta-value>14</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-toc-levels</meta-name><meta-value>0</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-product</meta-name><meta-value>ArchiveJournal</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>numbering-style</meta-name><meta-value>Unnumbered</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-grants-type</meta-name><meta-value>Regular</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>metadata-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>abstract-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>bodypdf-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>bodyhtml-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>bibliography-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>esm-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>online-first</meta-name><meta-value>true</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pdf-file-reference</meta-name><meta-value>BodyRef/PDF/41427_2010_Article_BFam2010133.pdf</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>target-type</meta-name><meta-value>OnlinePDF</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pdf-type</meta-name><meta-value>Typeset</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-type</meta-name><meta-value>BriefCommunication</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-primary</meta-name><meta-value>Materials Science</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Materials Science, general</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Biomaterials</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Optical and Electronic Materials</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Structural Materials</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Energy Systems</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Surface and Interface Science, Thin Films</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>open-access</meta-name><meta-value>false</meta-value></custom-meta></custom-meta-group></article-meta><notes notes-type="Misc"><p>This research highlight has been approved by the author of the original article and all empirical data contained within has been provided by said author.</p></notes></front><body><p id="Par2">Graphene — an atomic layer of carbon atoms arranged in a honeycomb lattice — has many properties that attract scientists and technologists alike. Among them, the combination of high electrical conductivity and very high (80%) transparency makes graphene an ideal candidate for the fabrication of transparent electrodes. Hongwei Zhu, Kunlin Wang and colleagues from Tsinghua University in China<sup><xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR1">1</xref></sup> have now demonstrated the possibility of using graphene as a component of solar cells.</p><p id="Par3">Solar cells convert light energy to electrical energy by providing a structure in which positive and negative charges generated by exposure to sunlight separate and migrate in opposite directions. This movement of charge generates a photocurrent, effectively transforming the energy of light into electricity, and silicon is the material that at present provides the most efficient rates of energy conversion. However, silicon is expensive, and squeezing higher efficiencies out of silicon-based solar cells has proved a challenge. Zhu and his colleagues predicted that placing a graphene film on the silicon would produce a Schottky junction — a diode-like potential barrier more typically associated with the interface between metals and semiconductors. In this carbon-on-silicon structure (Fig. 1), light passes through the transparent graphene film to the silicon layer, where it induces the formation of electron–hole pairs. These charge pairs then separate, with the electrons moving toward the silicon, and the holes toward the graphene.<fig id="Figa" position="anchor"><caption xml:lang="en"><p>Fig. 1: Schematic representation of a graphene-on-silicon solar cell. Photogenerated electrons (e<sup>–</sup>) and holes (h<sup>+</sup>) are separated and driven towards the silicon and graphene layers, respectively.</p></caption><graphic specific-use="web" mime-subtype="JPEG" xlink:href="MediaObjects/41427_2010_Article_BFam2010133_Figa_HTML.jpg" position="anchor"/></fig></p><p id="Par4">The researchers examined several devices of different sizes, and predicted reasonable energy conversion efficiency of 1.6% — lower than that for other carbon-on-silicon devices (5–7%) but with considerable scope for improvement. The main advantage of graphene over other carbon structures such as amorphous carbon or carbon nanotubes is that it covers the silicon surface uniformly while maintaining high transparency. “Further improvements in cell efficiency can be expected by optimizing the crystallinity and surface flatness of the graphene, by band-gap engineering, and by incorporating other photoactive materials,” says Zhu.</p><p id="Par5">The graphene-based solar cells are compatible with existing semiconductor technologies, and Zhu is optimistic that the cells could be used as power supplies in silicon-based integrated circuits. “This photovoltaic concept opens a new opportunity to develop carbon-based solar cells and can also be extended to other semiconducting materials instead of silicon,” says Zhu.</p></body><back><ref-list id="Bib1"><title>References</title><ref-list><ref id="CR1"><label>1</label><mixed-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Li</surname><given-names>Xinming</given-names></name><name><surname>Zhu</surname><given-names>Hongwei</given-names></name><name><surname>Wang</surname><given-names>Kunlin</given-names></name><name><surname>Cao</surname><given-names>Anyuan</given-names></name><name><surname>Wei</surname><given-names>Jinquan</given-names></name><name><surname>Li</surname><given-names>Chunyan</given-names></name><name><surname>Jia</surname><given-names>Yi</given-names></name><name><surname>Li</surname><given-names>Zhen</given-names></name><name><surname>Li</surname><given-names>Xiao</given-names></name><name><surname>Wu</surname><given-names>Dehai</given-names></name></person-group><article-title xml:lang="en">Graphene-On-Silicon Schottky Junction Solar Cells</article-title><source>Advanced Materials</source><year>2010</year><volume>22</volume><issue>25</issue><fpage>2743</fpage><lpage>2748</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="other" assigning-authority="ChemPort ( Chemical Abstract Service )">1:CAS:528:DC%2BC3cXovVCktL4%3D</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1002/adma.200904383</pub-id></mixed-citation></ref></ref-list></ref-list></back></article></records><facets><facet name="subject"><facet-value coun